ple have heard the hype by now, but what are the real reasons why you should seriously consider this change now? By 2013, Gartner Research predicts that at least 75% of customer-focused call centers will use a form of the cloud in their call centers and the industry is about to go through one of its fastest transitions ever. The barrier to running a top grade call center has just gotten a whole lot lower, folks.\r\n\r\n<strong>1. Cost Reduction</strong>\r\n\r\nThe total technology cost consists of licenses, maintenance fees and of course all hardware required to support operations. You will not need any special hardware on your end, just internet connected computers with headsets. Yup, no more capex. But wait, there is more: What about the specialised IT staff required to maintain your systems? Without infrastructure on your end, you might just save some staff cost here as well. Most cloud based systems charge per seat per month with a minimum investment up front\r\n\r\n<strong>2. Scalability/Flexibility</strong>\r\n\r\nA cloud solution can be scaled infinitely (well, almost) to your needs. Just made an acquisition or gotten a large new campaign? Extra capacity is just a few keystrokes away. Leading cloud providers can even offer hosting in various worldwide locations to suit your requirements. The flexibility is also great when you do campaign-based work and staff volumes can change a lot from month to month, as you would only pay for what you actually need. And yeah – leading cloud based providers offer plans without contracts, which means you are not locked in.\r\n\r\n<strong>3. Simplicity/Productivity</strong>\r\n\r\nSimplicity and its cousin productivity come as a result of how most cloud based systems are “solution centric” (just quoting Gartner).The best cloud based systems allow you as a business manager/operations manager to configure the system, monitor performance and generate reports all by yourself. No need to wait for other departments to extract data or load information. The operation is also a lot faster than with a more traditional system. Run better campaigns with real time access to all key campaign metrics and recordings, and let your clients access the system directly to see their own custom reports. Access or change any information from your iPad when you are having a coffee at the airport and correct mistakes before it’s too late. Enjoy.\r\n\r\n<strong>4. Combined Systems</strong>\r\n\r\nThe trend of combining various call center technologies into larger suites of products started way before the cloud based systems entered, but the rules of the game have just changed dramatically. Not only do cloud based systems make it easier to integrate call recordings, CRM, work force management, QA tools, reporting, call distribution, IVR, call monitoring, email and all other key tools into one, but it also opens up new opportunities, of which many are still not fully explored. Examples include real time information sourcing from online sources (people data, map data, social media updates etc.), data analytics, and a whole lot more. How about integrating the latest sports scores when you are calling on a Monday night, or knowing that the world’s biggest sausage pie was just made in the town on your next caller?\r\n\r\n<strong>5. Business Continuity</strong>\r\n\r\nProcedures for redundancy, backups and disaster recovery are not just pricey, but also attract significant risk as there are a number of factors that may go wrong. You may not be able to recover they data fully from backups, your extra dialler may not work that well, you may not have a full fledged facility to move to in case of flooding, fire, burglary (or all three at once of course). Welcome cloud based systems, where backups are done automatically, where systems are redundant and hosted in multiple locations and where your staff can access the system from any site, including their own kitchen when required. No more down time and no more data loss. Ever.','Top 5 reasons to go cloud','','publish','closed','open','','top-5-reasons-to-go-cloud-2','','','2013-06-18 14:23:30','2013-06-18 14:23:30','',0,'http://localhost:8080/restorewp/?p=1421',0,'post','',0),(1422,5,'2013-06-18 14:01:29','2013-06-18 14:01:29','Most people have heard the hype by now, but what are the real reasons why you should seriously consider this change now? By 2013, Gartner Research predicts that at least 75% of customer-focused call centers will use a form of the cloud in their call centers and the industry is about to go through one of its fastest transitions ever. The barrier to running a top grade call center has just gotten a whole lot lower, folks.\n\n<strong>1. Cost Reduction</strong>\n\nThe total technology cost consists of licenses, maintenance fees and of course all hardware required to support operations. You will not need any special hardware on your end, just internet connected computers with headsets. Yup, no more capex. But wait, there is more: What about the specialised IT staff required to maintain your systems? Without infrastructure on your end, you might just save some staff cost here as well. Most cloud based systems charge per seat per month with a minimum investment up front\n\n<strong>2. Scalability/Flexibility</strong>\n\nA cloud solution can be scaled infinitely (well, almost) to your needs. Just made an acquisition or gotten a large new campaign? Extra capacity is just a few keystrokes away. Leading cloud providers can even offer hosting in various worldwide locations to suit your requirements. The flexibility is also great when you do campaign-based work and staff volumes can change a lot from month to month, as you would only pay for what you actually need. And yeah – leading cloud based providers offer plans without contracts, which means you are not locked in.\n\n<strong>3. Simplicity/Productivity</strong>\n\nSimplicity and its cousin productivity come as a result of how most cloud based systems are “solution centric